<td id="title_text"><h1><a title="Bulking Index" class="currentChild" href="Bulking_Index">Bulking Index</a></h1></td>



</tr></table>
</td>
</tr></table></div>



<div id="content" class="content wikipage" lang="en" dir="ltr">
<p id="l1">
A term used in book manufacturing which designates a paper's thickness (called <a title="Bulk" href="Bulk">bulk</a> or <a title="Caliper" href="Caliper">caliper</a>) in inches per pound of <a title="Basis Weight" href="Basis_Weight">basis weight</a>. It is obtained by dividing the thickness of a single sheet by the paper's basis weight. Bulking index is used to compare the bulk of papers having the same <a title="Basic Size" href="Basic_Size">basic size</a> and varying basis weights. (See <a title="Bulk" href="Bulk">Bulk</a> and <a title="Basis Weight" href="Basis_Weight">Basis Weight</a>.) 
</p>
